SIMPLE: nick
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nick
<hw>Nick</hw> <pr>(n⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>nicor</ets> a marine monster; akin to D. <ets>nikker</ets> a water
spite, Icel. <ets>nykr</ets>, ONG. <ets>nihhus</ets> a crocodile, G.
<ets>nix</ets> a water sprite; cf. Gr. <grk>ni`ptein</grk> to wash, Skr.
<ets>nij</ets>. Cf. <er>Nix</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Northern Myth.)</fld>
<def>An evil spirit of the waters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Old Nick</b></col>, <cd>the evil one; the devil.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nick
<hw>Nick</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to <er>Nock</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A notch cut into something</def>; <specif>as:</specif>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A score for keeping an account; a reckoning.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A notch cut
crosswise in the shank of a type, to assist a compositor in placing it
properly in the stick, and in distribution.</def> <rj><au>W.
Savage.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A broken or indented place
in any edge or surface; <as>as, <ex>nicks</ex> in a china plate; a
<ex>nick</ex> in the table top</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A particular point or place considered as marked by
a nick; the exact point or critical moment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To cut it off in the very <qex>nick</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>nick</qex> of time is the critical occasion for the
gaining of a point.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Nick
<hw>Nick</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Nicked</conjf> <pr>(n⟦icr⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Nicking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a nick or
nicks in; to notch; to keep count of or upon by nicks; <as>as, to
<ex>nick</ex> a stick, tally, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mar; to deface; to make ragged, as by cutting
nicks or notches in; to create a nick{2} in, deliberately or
accidentally; <as>as, to <ex>nick</ex> the rim of a
teacup</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>And thence proceed to <qex>nicking</qex> sashes.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The itch of his affection should not then⟦br⟧
Have <qex>nicked</qex> his captainship.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To suit or fit into, as by a correspondence of
nicks; to tally with.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Words <qex>nicking</qex> and resembling one another are applicable
to different significations.</q> <rj><qau>Camden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hit at, or in, the nick; to touch rightly; to
strike at the precise point or time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The just season of doing things must be <qex>nicked</qex>, and all
accidents improved.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make a cross cut or cuts on the under side of
(the tail of a horse, in order to make him carry it higher).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Nick
<hw>Nick</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To nickname; to style.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For Warbeck, as you <qex>nick</qex> him, came to me.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nickar tree</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Nickar nut</ent>⟦br⟧
